Continuous positive airway pressure [http://www.apneatherapy.com CPAP] is a method of respiratory ventilation used primarily in the treatment of sleep apnea and various lung diseases. [http://www.apneatherapy.com CPAP] ventilation can also be used during the "weaning off" period of a ventilated intensive care patient, but this will not be covered in this article.

A device called a [http://www.apneatherapy.com CPAP] machine, which is basically a pump, is used to pass a controlled stream of air into the airway of the sleeping patient, splinting the airway (keeping it open under air pressure) so that unobstructed breathing becomes possible, reducing and/or preventing apneas and hypopneas.